      <section name="Installation">
       <span class='shortdesc'>How to install Hippo CMS</span>

        <span class='review'>Check if all statements true.</span>

        <p>
          To run Hippo CMS, a 
          <span class='hidden_index' id='servlet_container'/><span class='index' id='java_servlet_container'>Java servlet container</span> 
          is sufficient. 
          <span class='hidden_index' id='application_server'/><span class='index' id='java_application_server'>Java application servers</span> 
          include the functionality of Java servlect containers,
          and have the advantage that they allow for adding new features, without the need
          for a reinstall (because they accept EAR packages).
        </p>
        <p>
          Hippo supplies a Java <span class='index' id='WAR'>WAR</span> package to deploy in a Java servlet container and
          a more sophisticated <span class='index' id='EAR'>EAR</span> package to deploy in a Java application server. 
	</p>
        <p>Java servlet containers are for example: 
           <a href='http://jetty.mortbay.com/jetty/'>Jetty</a>, 
           <a href='http://tomcat.apache.org/'>Apache Tomcat</a>.
           Java application servers are for example: 
           <a href='https://glassfish.dev.java.net/public/users.html'>Sun Glassfish</a>, 
           <a href='http://www.jboss.org/'>JBoss</a>,
           <a href='http://www-01.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/'>IBM WebSphere Application Server (WAS)</a>,
           <a href='http://www.bea.com/framework.jsp?CNT=index.htm&amp;FP=/content/products/weblogic/server'>Oracle Bea WebLogic Server</a>.
        </p>
      </section>
